  "articleSummary": "The article \"The Priority Trap\" critiques the use of rigid, predefined priority dropdowns (e.g., P1-P4) in task management systems like Jira, arguing that they fail to adapt to dynamic organizational needs and lead to inflation of priority labels (e.g., P00). It frames this as a \"trap\" where teams endlessly add higher-priority tiers, creating chaos akin to \"z-index wars\" in front-end development, and highlights the confusion between *Priority* (strategic importance) and *Severity* (urgency). The tone blends analysis with dry humor, using metaphors like \"Engineering Theater\" and \"Bizzaro Trophy Room\" to critique bloated backlogs. The author advocates for flexible alternatives—numerical scales, composite scores, or dynamic frameworks like MoSCoW—to better reflect shifting priorities and reduce backlog bloat. Targeted at software teams and managers, the piece urges rethinking prioritization as a fluid, human-driven process rather than a static, hierarchical system.",
